|21|W|region:CA-ON_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <ref name=climate/>\n|elevation_m            = 192\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of P postal codes of Canada|P6A to P6C]]\n|area_code              = [[Area code 705|(705) and (249)]]<ref>[http://www.sootoday.com/content/news/full_story.asp?StoryNumber=50379 \"Time to say goodbye to seven-digit calls\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120152913/http://sootoday.com/content/news/full_story.asp?StoryNumber=50379 |date=2011-01-20 }}, Sootoday</ref>\n|blank_name             = Highways\n|blank_info             =  {{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=ON|ON|17}}\n*{{jct|state=ON|ON|550}}\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|75}} }}\n|website                = {{url|saultstemarie.ca}}\n|footnotes              = [[Census agglomeration|CA]] rank:&nbsp;[[List of the 100 largest metropolitan areas in Canada|46th in Canada]]<br/>Municipal rank:&nbsp;[[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|66th in Canada]]\n}}\n\n'''Sault Ste. Marie''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|u\u02d0|_|s|e\u026a|n|t|_|m|\u0259|\u02c8|r|i\u02d0}} \"Soo Saint Marie\") is a city on the [[St. Marys River (Michigan\u2013Ontario)|St. Marys River]] in [[Ontario]], Canada, close to the [[Canada\u2013United States border|U.S.-Canada border]]. It is the seat of the [[Algoma District]] and the third largest city in [[Northern Ontario]], after [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]] and [[Thunder Bay]].\n\nThe [[Ojibwe]], the indigenous [[Anishinaabe]] inhabitants of the area, call this area ''Baawitigong'', meaning \"place of the rapids.\" They used this as a regional meeting place during [[freshwater whitefish|whitefish]] season in the St. Mary's Rapids. (The [[English language|anglicized]] form of this name, Bawating, is used in institutional and geographic names in the area.)\n\nTo the south, across the river, is the United States and the [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Michigan city of the same name]]. These two communities were one city until a new treaty after the [[War of 1812]] established the border between Canada and the United States in this area at the St. Mary's River. In the 21st century, the two cities are joined by the [[Sault Ste. Marie International Bridge|International Bridge]], which connects [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|Interstate 75]] on the Michigan side, and Huron Street (and former Ontario Secondary Highway 550B) on the Ontario side. Shipping traffic in the [[Great Lakes]] system bypasses the Saint Mary's Rapids via the American [[Soo Locks]], the world's busiest canal in terms of tonnage that passes through it, while smaller recreational and tour boats use the Canadian [[Sault Ste. Marie Canal]].\n\nFrench colonists referred to the rapids on the river as ''Les Saults de Ste. Marie'' and the village name was derived from that. The rapids and cascades of the St. Mary's River descend more than {{Convert|20|ft|abbr=on|0}} from the level of Lake Superior to the level of the lower lakes. Hundreds of years ago, this slowed shipping traffic, requiring an overland portage of boats and cargo from one lake to the other.  The entire name translates to \"Saint Mary's Rapids\" or \"Saint Mary's Falls\". The word ''sault'' is pronounced {{IPA-fr|so|}} in French, and {{IPAc-en|s|u\u02d0}} in the English pronunciation of the city name.<ref>[http://www.sault-sainte-marie.mi.us/history.htm \"History\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801135609/http://sault-sainte-marie.mi.us/history.htm |date=2013-08-01 }}, Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan website</ref> Residents of the city are called ''Saultites''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saultstar.com/2015/06/15/saultite-receives-honour-from-the-queen|title=Saultite receives honour from the Queen|first=|last=nurun.com|date=|website=Sault Star|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSault Ste. Marie is bordered to the east by the [[Rankin Location 15D, Ontario|Rankin]]<!-- It's inhabited by the Batchawana First Nation, but the name of the *reserve* is Rankin, not Batchawana. --> and [[Garden River 14, Ontario|Garden River]] [[First Nation]] reserves, and to the west by [[Prince, Ontario|Prince Township]]. To the north, the city is bordered by an [[Unorganized North Algoma District|unincorporated portion of Algoma District]], which includes the [[local services board (Ontario)|local services boards]] of [[Aweres, Ontario|Aweres]], [[Batchawana Bay, Ontario|Batchawana Bay]], [[Goulais and District, Ontario|Goulais and District]], [[Peace Tree, Ontario|Peace Tree]] and [[Searchmont, Ontario|Searchmont]]. The city's [[census agglomeration]], including the townships of [[Laird, Ontario|Laird]], [[Prince, Ontario|Prince]] and [[Macdonald, Meredith and Aberdeen Additional]] and the [[Indian reserve|First Nations reserves]] of [[Garden River, Ontario|Garden River]] and [[Rankin Location 15D, Ontario|Rankin]], had a total population of 79,800 in 2011.\n\nNative American settlements, mostly of [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]]-speaking peoples, existed here for more than 500 years. In the late 17th century, French [[Jesuit Missions in North America|Jesuit missionaries]] established a mission at the First Nations village. This was followed by development of a fur trading post and larger settlement, as traders, trappers and Native Americans were attracted to the community. It was considered one community and part of Canada until after the [[War of 1812]] and settlement of the border between Canada and the US at the Ste. Mary's River. At that time, the US prohibited British traders from any longer operating in its territory, and the areas separated by the river began to develop as two communities, both named Sault Ste. Marie.<ref>[http://www.thenorthview.org/history/saultdesaintemarie.html \"Sault Ste. Marie \u2013 history\"], The North View, accessed 20 Dec 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512000716/http://www.thenorthview.org/history/saultdesaintemarie.html |date=May 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fishing at Saint Mary's River, Sault Sainte Marie, Michigan, 1901.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.3<!--width for very low image-->|[[Ojibwe]] fishermen in the St. Marys Rapids, 1901]]\n[[File:Sault Ste Marie Museum 8.JPG|thumb|Sault Ste. Marie Museum in downtown Sault Ste. Marie]]\n\nAfter the visit of [[\u00c9tienne Br\u00fbl\u00e9]] in 1623, the [[France|French]] called it \"Sault de Gaston\" in honour of [[Gaston, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]], the brother of King [[Louis XIII of France]]. In 1668, French [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] missionaries renamed it as '''Sault Sainte Marie''', and established a mission settlement (present-day [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan]]) on the river's south bank.\n\nLater, a [[fur trade|fur trading]] post was established and the settlement expanded to include both sides of the river.  Sault Ste. Marie is one of the [[List of North American cities by year of foundation|oldest]] French settlements in North America.  It was at the crossroads of the 3,000-mile [[Canadian canoe routes (early)#Saint Lawrence River basin|fur trade route]], which stretched from [[Montreal]] to Sault Ste. Marie and to the North country above Lake Superior. A cosmopolitan, mixed population of Europeans, First Nations peoples, and [[M\u00e9tis people|M\u00e9tis]] lived at the village spanning the river.<ref>[http://www.thenorthview.org/history/saultdesaintemarie.html  \"Sault Ste. Marie \u2013 history\"], ''The North View'', accessed 20 Dec 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512000716/http://www.thenorthview.org/history/saultdesaintemarie.html |date=May 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe city name originates from ''Saults de Sainte-Marie'', archaic French for \"Saint Mary's Falls\", a reference to the [[rapid]]s of Saint Marys River. Etymologically, the word ''sault'' comes from an archaic spelling of ''saut'' (from ''sauter''), which translates most accurately in this usage to the English word ''cataract''.  This in turn derives from the [[French language|French]] word for \"leap\" or \"jump\" (similar to ''[[somersault]]''). Citations dating back to 1600 use the ''sault'' spelling to mean a cataract, waterfall or rapids. In modern French, however, the words ''chutes'' or ''rapides'' are more usual. ''Sault'' survives almost exclusively in geographic names dating from the 17th century. (See also [[Long Sault, Ontario]], [[Kahnawake|Sault St. Louis, Quebec]], and [[Grand Falls, New Brunswick|Grand Falls/Grand-Sault, New Brunswick]], three other place names where \"sault\" also carries this meaning.)\n\nTraders regularly interacted with tribes from around the Great Lakes, and Scots-British fur trader [[John Johnston (fur trader)|John Johnston]], his Ojibwe wife and multi-racial were prominent among all societies here in the late eighteenth century. Their daughter, [[Jane Johnston Schoolcraft]] married [[Henry Rowe Schoolcraft]], a US Indian agent and early ethnographer, and they had children. She has been recognized as the first Native American poet and writer in the United States.\n\nThis fluid environment changed during and after the [[War of 1812]] between Britain and the United States. Trade dropped during the war and on July 20, 1814 an American force destroyed the [[North West Company]] depot on the north shore of the St. Marys River. Since the Americans were unable to capture [[Fort Mackinac]], the British forces retained control of Sault Ste. Marie.<ref>Mary Ellen Perkins (ed.) 'Discover your heritage: A Guide to Provincial Plaques in Ontario' Natural Heritage (Jun 30 1989) {{ISBN|0920474500}} \u2013 plaque on eastern end of Canadian locks, Huron Street, Saint Ste. Marie</ref> As noted, after the war with a new border defined, the US closed its territory to British Canadian traders, shutting off much interaction.\n\n[[File:Red River Expedition cairn 2.JPG|thumb|right|[[Cairn]] commemorating the Wolseley Expedition to quell the [[Red River Rebellion]].]]\n[[File:Turning the first sod at Sault Ste-Marie July 30th 1890, on the first publicly owned power canal constructed in Canada, for general distribution of power for industrial purposes (HS85-10-41465).jpg|thumb|right|Turning the first sod ceremony for the construction of the [[Sault Ste. Marie Canal]], 30 July 1890.]]\nIn 1870, the United States refused to give the steamer ''Chicona'', carrying Colonel [[Garnet Wolseley]], permission to pass through the locks at Sault Ste Marie. In order to control their own water passage, the Canadians constructed the [[Sault Ste. Marie Canal]], which was completed in 1895.<ref>Mary Ellen Perkins (ed.) 'Discover your heritage: A Guide to Provincial Plaques in Ontario' Natural Heritage (Jun 30 1989) {{ISBN|0920474500}} \u2013 plaque near Canadian locks, Huron Street, Saint Ste. Marie</ref>\n\nSault Ste. Marie, Ontario was incorporated as a town in 1887 and a city in 1912. The town gained brief international notoriety in 1911 in the trial of [[Angelina Napolitano]], the first person in Canada to use the [[battered woman defence]] for murder.<ref name=\"Dictionary\">{{cite DCB |title=Napolitano (Neapolitano), Angelina |first=Franca |last=Iacovetta |volume=15 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/napolitano_angelina_15E.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], and particularly after the US was attacked at [[Pearl Harbor]] in 1941, government concern turned to protection of the locks and shipping channel at Sault Ste. Marie. A substantial military presence was established to protect the locks from a possible attack by [[Nazi Germany|Nazi German]] aircraft from the north. The recent development of long-range bombers increased fears of a sudden air raid.  Military strategists studied polar projection maps, which indicated that the air distance from occupied [[Norway]] to the town was about the same as the distance from Norway to New York. That direct route of about {{Convert|3000|mi|abbr=on}} is over terrain where there were few observers and long winter nights.\n\nA joint Canadian and US committee called the \"Permanent Joint Board on Defence\" drove the installation of anti-aircraft defence and associated units of the [[United States Army Air Forces]] and [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] to defend the locks.  An anti-aircraft training facility was established {{convert|100|km|abbr=on}} north of Sault Ste. Marie on the shores of [[Great Lakes|Lake Superior]].  [[Barrage balloon]]s were installed, and early warning radar bases were established at five locations in northern Ontario ([[Kapuskasing]], [[Cochrane, Ontario|Cochrane]], [[Hearst, Ontario|Hearst]], [[CFS Armstrong|Armstrong (Thunder Bay District)]], and [[Nakina, Ontario|Nakina]])<ref>{{cite book | title = Military Relations Between the United States and Canada 1939\u20131945 | last = Dziuban | first = Stanley W. | year = 1970 | page = 196 | url = http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-SS-Canada/USA-SS-Canada-7.html | publisher = [[United States Army Center of Military History]] | access-date = 2010-06-30 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100410013357/http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-SS-Canada/USA-SS-Canada-7.html | archivedate = 2010-04-10 }}</ref> to watch for incoming aircraft. Military personnel were established to guard sensitive parts of the transportation infrastructure.  A little over one year later, in January 1943, most of these facilities and defences were deemed excessive and removed, save a reduced military base at Sault Ste. Marie.\n\nThe first [[Algerine-class minesweeper|''Algerine''-class minesweeper]] in the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] was named [[HMCS Sault Ste. Marie (J334)|HMCS ''Sault Ste. Marie'' (J334)]] after the city. It was laid down in 1942 and acted as a convoy in the [[Battle of the Atlantic]].\n\nOn January 29, 1990, Sault Ste. Marie became a flashpoint in the [[Meech Lake Accord]] constitutional debate when council passed a resolution declaring English as the city's official language<ref>''Canadian Annual Review of Politics and Public Affairs, 1990'', David Leyton-Brown (ed.), p.135. \"On the language front, a major headache for the government began when the Sault Ste Marie City Council, under pressure from the Alliance for the Preservation of English in Canada, declared English as its official language.\"</ref> and the sole language for provision of municipal services. French speakers had already gained the use of French as an official language for government services.<ref>''Crosswords: Language, Education and Ethnicity in French Ontario'', Monica Heller, p. 79</ref> The city had a sizable French-speaking population and these residents objected strongly to the council's action. The [[Sault Ste. Marie language resolution]] was not the first of its kind in Ontario, but the municipality was the largest to have passed such a resolution and the first to do so despite its sizable [[Franco-Ontarian]] population.<ref>Heller, ''Crosswords'', p. 80</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nSault Ste. Marie has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfb'') with cold, snowy winters and warm summers that are moderated to some extent by [[Lake Superior]]. Winters are cold but are milder than some inland places.<ref name=climate>{{Cite web |url=http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=4093&lang=e&dCode=1&province=ONT&provBut=&month1=0&month2=12 |title=Canadian Climate Normals 1971\u20132000 |publisher=Environment Canada |access-date=2012-05-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010042513/http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=4093&lang=e&dCode=1&province=ONT&provBut=&month1=0&month2=12 |archivedate=2011-10-10 }}</ref> Temperatures drop below {{convert|-20|C}} 24 days per year. Summers are warm with a July high of {{convert|24.0|C}} and temperatures above {{convert|30|C}} occur 4 days per year.<ref name=climate /> The average annual precipitation is {{convert|889|mm|abbr=on|1}}, which is fairly evenly distributed throughout the year; February is the driest month, and the autumn months of September to November are the wettest months.<ref name=climate /> The highest temperature ever recorded in Sault Ste. Marie was {{convert|37.2|C}} on 3 July 1921,<ref name=\"July 1921\">\n{{cite web\n |publisher   = [[Environment Canada]]\n |url         = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1889-03-01%7C1933-12-31&mlyRange=1889-01-01%7C1933-12-01&StationID=4094&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&Month=7&Day=12&txtStationName=sault+ste+m&timeframe=2&Year=1921\n |title       = July 1921\n |work        = Canadian Climate Data\n |access-date  = 25 March 2016\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160807215217/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1889-03-01%7C1933-12-31&mlyRange=1889-01-01%7C1933-12-01&StationID=4094&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&Month=7&Day=12&txtStationName=sault+ste+m&timeframe=2&Year=1921\n |archivedate = 7 August 2016\n}}</ref> while the record low was {{convert|-41.1|C}} on 26 January 1927.<ref name=\"January 1927\">\n{{cite web\n |publisher   = [[Environment Canada]]\n |url         = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1889-03-01%7C1933-12-31&mlyRange=1889-01-01%7C1933-12-01&StationID=4094&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&txtStationName=sault+ste+m&timeframe=2&Year=1927&Month=1\n |title       = January 1927\n |work        = Canadian Climate Data\n |access-date  = 25 March 2016\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160807180131/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1889-03-01%7C1933-12-31&mlyRange=1889-01-01%7C1933-12-01&StationID=4094&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&txtStationName=sault+ste+m&timeframe=2&Year=1927&Month=1\n |archivedate = 7 August 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|collapsed = \n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|location = [[Sault Ste. Marie Airport]], 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1889\u2013present\n|Jan maximum humidex = 7.8\n|Feb maximum humidex = 8.7\n|Mar maximum humidex = 28.0\n|Apr maximum humidex = 31.6\n|May maximum humidex = 38.6\n|Jun maximum humidex = 40.9\n|Jul maximum humidex = 42.9\n|Aug maximum humidex = 42.7\n|Sep maximum humidex = 39.5\n|Oct maximum humidex = 34.4\n|Nov maximum humidex = 21.6\n|Dec maximum humidex = 19.2\n|year maximum humidex = 42.9\n|Jan record high C = 7.8\n|Feb record high C = 12.0\n|Mar record high C = 26.7\n|Apr record high C = 30.0\n|May record high C = 32.3\n|Jun record high C = 34.4\n|Jul record high C = 37.2\n|Aug record high C = 36.1\n|Sep record high C = 35.0\n|Oct record high C = 27.8\n|Nov record high C = 21.7\n|Dec record high C = 15.4\n|year record high C = 37.2\n|Jan high C = -5.0\n|Feb high C = -3.6\n|Mar high C = 1.2\n|Apr high C = 9.0\n|May high C = 16.4\n|Jun high C = 21.4\n|Jul high C = 24.2\n|Aug high C = 23.4\n|Sep high C = 18.9\n|Oct high C = 11.6\n|Nov high C = 4.5\n|Dec high C = -1.8\n|year high C = 10.0\n|Jan mean C = -9.9\n|Feb mean C = -9.0\n|Mar mean C = -4.2\n|Apr mean C = 3.6\n|May mean C = 10.0\n|Jun mean C = 15.0\n|Jul mean C = 17.9\n|Aug mean C = 17.5\n|Sep mean C = 13.5\n|Oct mean C = 7.1\n|Nov mean C = 1.0\n|Dec mean C = -5.7\n|year mean C = 4.7\n|Jan low C = -14.8\n|Feb low C = -14.3\n|Mar low C = -9.6\n|Apr low C = -1.8\n|May low C = 3